04357nam a22006975i 9789633864975DE-B159720230228020105.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||230228t20022002hu     fo  d z      eng d  a9789633864975  a(DE-B1597)633608  a(OCoLC)1338021255  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  ahucHU 4aPG7158.I8bA25 2002eb 7aLIT0000002bisacsh04a891.8/53732231 aIwaszkiewicz, Jarosław, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut14aThe Birch Grove and Other Stories /cJarosław Iwaszkiewicz. 1aBudapest ;aNew York : bCentral European University Press, c[2002] 4c©2002  a1 online resource (288 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aCEU Press Classics (formerly Central European Classics)00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tIntroduction -- tA New Love -- tTh e Witko Girls -- tThe Birch Grove -- tThe Mill on the River Utrata -- tCentral European Classics0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aJaroslaw Iwaszkiewicz's work is familiar to every Polish reader, yet remains unknown to the outside world. The stories in this selection were all written in the 1930s, and provide an extraordinary evocation of Poland's first brief era of independence between the wars. They are also timeless sonatas of love and loss. In 'A New Love', Iwaszkiewicz uses masterful brevity to take a wry, comical look at the illusion of romance from the viewpoint of a jaded, cynical lover. One of his best-known works, 'The Wilko Girls', tells of a middle-aged man's quest to recover his lost youth in the aftermath of the First World War, which has left him psychologically scarred. He travels to the scene of his pre-war summer holidays in the eastern borderlands, where he renews his friendship with the fascinating sisters whom he knew when they were girls. But no one is the same and nothing can be as it was. 'The Birch Grove' is the moving story of a woodsman who, spiritually destroyed by the death of his wife, has buried himself away in an isolated forest. When his lively younger brother unexpectedly comes to stay, his self-centred peace is disrupted. But his brother has come home to die. The lives of two young men, one a deeply religious poet, the other a sceptical, worldly estate owner, are touchingly contrasted in 'The Mill on the River Utrata'. Confirming these stories' central place in Polish cultural history, 'The Wilko Girls' and 'The Birch Grove' were made into classic films by Andrzej Wajda, Poland's leading director.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 28. Feb 2023) 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / General.2bisacsh  aA New Love.  aThe Mill on the River Utrata.  aWilko Girls.1 aGanon Asb, Timothy, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKołakowski, Leszek, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLloyd-Jones, Antonia, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertCentral European University Press eBook-Package 2013-1998z978311078055040uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9789633864975423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9789633864975/original  a978-3-11-078055-0  Central European University Press eBook-Package 2013-1998c1998d2013  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_LT  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_LT  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK